content.description: Use key footwork on nice edges up the short face with crystals to top out. This is a good way to wake up your feet for other slab problems in the area.
content.location: Just head straight back through the 'Corridor', and you'll walk right up to this short, slabby face with slightly worn and rubbed pinkish edges at the far end (west).

content.description: Either start by scrambling up the adjacent block to the right to gain the crack, or jam it ground-up. This is tricky and sustained with a nice crux in a compact size.
content.protection: A couple pieces of hand- or finger-size and perhaps TCUs or stoppers for finicky placements. There are bolted anchors on top with an easy walkoff.
content.location:
Head north from the parking pulloff into the valley past

Easy Hops

following the faint trail. This large formation will be obvious on your left and has a set of TR anchors visible. Look for the first striking splitter on the left side of the main wall.

content.description: Climb the crack to the bisected seam that forms the top of the "T" with a few final committing moves to top out. It is a highball. You can bail early right, which contrives it a bit and loses the 4th star IMO. Otherwise, this is classic.
content.protection: Pads and a spotter. I am not sure if this can be toproped.
content.location:
Head up the valley north past

Easy Hops

, and pass the large block with cracks and toprope anchors on your left. Look for a small valley breaking left (west), and follow it slightly uphill. This will be on the left as you ascend the valley. The photo should help.

content.description: Step up onto the small boulder at the base of the low angled slab. Make one easy friction step and reach up high to a bomber flake. Top out above using some crystals. Scoot down and easily jump off to the boulder on the right.
content.protection: Half of one pad over the small boulder directly below the face and maybe a goalie. A fall would probably be bad, mmkay.
content.location:
This is just past

Handcrack

as you walk through the "Corridor" on the opposite (south) side. It has a waist high block at the base.

content.description: Muckle through small holds and one awesome sloper feature to a tall topout. This is enlivening!
content.protection: Pads and spotters, it is a highball with a sloped landing. Once above the sloper feature, I'd wager a fall would be severe.
content.location: From the pulloff below the corridor, head slightly right past a couple boulders(Easy Hops problem) into a small valley with a faint trail. Follow the trail about 5 minutes or so until this slab is encountered, which spans a good portion of hillside directly ahead up the valley. The line starts a bit right of center, more or less below the obvious sloper bump that's well above head height.

content.description: Get easily established on the slab, then work straight up through steep and thin face to the lip.
content.protection: Pads and a spotter. This is a tall problem over a slab and a sloped landing.
content.location:
It is on the big, scooped slab directly ahead of you when you park in the pulloff to the left of

The Disk

problem. The small trail to the "Corridor" leads uphill and left from this rock. Start a bit left of center.

content.description: Pull on to your choice of crimps and move up to a nice edge. Top out the sloping lip.
content.location:
This is uphill and out left (west) of The Corridor Area, just downhill of the

Layback Arete

.

content.description: This is one of the best face problems at this grade in the area, IMO. Start with good and obvious holds at head height. Move up to a pinch and climb straight up the face. Once on top, finish by tunneling left through a short 'cave traverse' or enjoy a last 10' of easy offwidth.
content.protection: A pad and spotter or two. The landing is good but slightly angled.
content.location:
When taking the short trail to the Corridor, break slightly left around and downhill from the first boulder with

Arete V4

, and follow along till you can round the corner of the last tall boulder on the right, just past a short offwidth crack with a 'Y' split. The problem goes up the west face. There is an easy offwidth/chimney by the left side of the problem that you exit through after topping out.

content.description: Sit start the slabby finger crack getting hands in near the sloped topout.
content.location: Along the lower faces of the corridor and above the road, look for a nice crack leaning slightly right.

content.description: Start with a high left hand on the arete. Smear on and match then layback to a cool deadpoint.
content.protection: Pads and spotters. Be aware of some crumbly rock on the face.
content.location: It is located uphill and west of The Corridor Area.

content.description: Start with finger jams and one foot kicked out behind to your left. Step up to establish yourself in the crack.
content.location: It is in the main corridor area.

content.description: This is a fun handcrack with an exciting topout. Cruiser hand jams lead to a sloping finish.
content.location:
It is the obvious, left-leaning hand crack just left of

Crack Traverse

.

content.description: From Down Under requires good foot work and is a fun, chill climb.
content.location:
From

Buttcrack

, V3, head 127 [degrees SE] 50 yards or so around the backside of the big boulder you see.

content.description: The big flake/disk near the road.  Traverse the edge using crystals on top.
content.location: Next to the road.

content.description: This is a short, mostly hands crack that steepens near the lip.
content.protection: A couple hand-size cams and maybe a couple smaller. There are NO BOLTED ANCHORS. You must build gear anchor in the horizontal (tricky hand sizes). There is an easy walk on/off.
content.location:
Head north from the parking pulloff into the valley past

Easy Hops

following the faint trail. This large formation will be obvious on your left and has a set of TR anchors visible. This route is right of the

Ten Plus Crack

, which has the bolted anchors above.

content.description: This has two short cracks of equal difficulty, although the left corner is more classic IMO.
content.protection: Pads or a piece of hand-size pro if you're not comfortable with the height. There is opportunity for a gear anchor on top. There is a walkoff.
content.location:
This is on the left side of the large formation, encountered on your left (west) following the faint trail through the valley past

Easy Hops

. Head north from the parking pulloff into the valley past

Easy Hops

following the faint trail. This large formation will be obvious on your left and has a set of TR anchors visible. Look for a right-facing corner and two cracks on the left side of the formation.

content.description: Climb the right-facing flake to a tall topout.
content.protection: Pads and spotters. Either downclimb the corner off to the right or downclimb the route. It is wise to scope out both options well before doing this.
content.location:
Head north from the parking pulloff into the valley past

Easy Hops

following the faint trail. This large formation will be obvious on your left and has a set of TR anchors visible. This problem is right of the second crack and climbs the flake to the high ledge.

content.description: This is a beautiful, low ball, overhanging crack. Wonderfully painful fist jams lead to jamming over a flaked roof. Sit start with great hands.
content.location: Take the right trail from the Pike National Forest sign on the north side of the road. Follow the trail up to the bottom of where the boulderfield begins, and it is one of the first boulders you will encounter. This is a north-facing crack in a sort of cave-like dugout.

content.description: Jump up (if you're short like me), and palm some good granite crystals. Mantel onto the small ledge, and it's over.
content.location:
It is on the boulder directly ahead when you park at the small pulloff to the left of The Disk Boulder. This is just right of

Slab Surfer

.

content.description: Reach high to crystals and pinches at the lowest end of the floating "disk". Traverse up and right to the juggy lip at the top, and rock over.
content.location: Just off the road, this is the immediate rock to the right of the pulloff. It is on the opposite side of where you park.

content.description: Start up the right-trending, hand crack for a couple moves.  Then, reach wide left into pockets hidden in the left traverse crack.  Pretty hard, due to the fact that there is virtually nothing for you to gain footing on.
content.location:
This is on the Corridor Boulder - the first rock on the right as you come up the approach trail.  It is across from

Arete

, V4.  It is the obvious, leftward-running, finger crack that starts with a short hand crack.

content.description: Climb the dirty, right-facing corner working slightly left to jugs up high on some bad rock.
content.location:
Go around right from

Flake Face

until you find this mungy, right-facing corner. This is used to descend from

Flake Face

.

content.description: Follow the obvious crack sit start. I removed the little brush coming out of the crack and cleaned it really nicely.
content.location:
Continue on Rampart Range Road till you reach the entering Pike National Forest on your right side and leaving Pike National Forest on your left. There is a pullout with little rocks on the right.

Continue on the trail past all the large boulders you see on your right and up a little more and right to the left of the trail.

14 [degrees North] from this spot about fifty yards is a really cool tree swing someone put up.

content.description: Start in the sharp crack on Gargoyle Rock, with minimal feet, continue up on crystals.
content.location: This is the first arete you see as you come up the hill on the trail.
